## CRASH PROMOTION GATE â€” LEGITIMATE CRASHES ONLY

Only put a reproducing sanitizer diagnostic under `{{ results_dir }}/crashes/CRASH-*` when it is a
legitimate crash testcase. The gate is **NOT** "the caller used only the inputs
the docs show in examples." Public APIs accept every value of their declared
parameter type by definition; if the implementation breaks on one of those
values, that is the bug, not a contract violation.

A crash is legitimate when ALL of the following hold:

1. **Public API entrypoint.** The trusted caller invokes a documented public
   function/CLI/IPC entry. Any value within the declared parameter type is
   fair game â€” the API contract is the type signature, not example values.
   Specifically, the following are LEGITIMATE attacker inputs, not contract
   violations:
   - negative, zero, or oversized integer fields in typed structs
     (`int rm_so = -1024`, `size_t len = SIZE_MAX`) â€” when that field is
     part of the untrusted input the library parses, NOT a size you chose
     to describe a buffer you allocated (see the caller-buffer rule below)
   - NULL pointers passed to functions that document them as nullable
     (or are silent about nullability)
   - malformed length prefixes, magic numbers, or version fields in
     serialized blobs, files, archives, IPC messages, network packets
   - fully-formed CLI flags with adversarial values (oversized integers,
     embedded NULs, locale-shifted bytes)
   - pointer arithmetic the API silently trusts (e.g., `re_endp` set
     before `pattern`, mismatched `pmatch[0].rm_so > rm_eo`)
   - ownership transfers when the public API documents no transfer (e.g.,
     calling a "borrow" API with a dangling pointer is caller misuse;
     calling a "take ownership" API with a valid pointer is not)
2. **Untrusted boundary.** The input-shaped part is the documented
   untrusted boundary: file bytes, packet bytes, web content, regex
   pattern, media stream, archive, IPC/message bytes, CLI input, struct
   fields of a public type, or an equivalent product input boundary.
3. **No internal-state mutation by the testcase.** The testcase does NOT
   mutate target-owned object internals, include private/test-only
   target code, switch allocators after target allocations exist,
   return lengths from a caller callback that the docs explicitly
   declare invalid (e.g. larger than the supplied buffer), or destroy
   an owner before using a dependent object in an order the public
   docs explicitly require.

   Re-entering the library through PUBLIC API from inside a public
   callback (e.g. calling `*_cleanup()` from inside a registered
   `LOCKFUNC` / `WRITE_CALLBACK` / `HEADER_CALLBACK`) is LEGITIMATE
   unless the callback's documentation explicitly prohibits re-entry.
   If the library fires the callback before establishing its own
   invariants (refcount, lifetime, init order) and the harness then
   triggers a UAF or use-of-uninit by calling a public function from
   inside the callback, that is a LIBRARY ordering bug â€” promote it.
   The fix is library-side: establish the invariant first, then fire
   the callback (or refuse re-entry from inside the library). A
   "caller contract" rejection requires you to *quote the documented
   prohibition*; silence in the docs means the contract is in-domain.

The distinction is "did the caller break a contract the docs state, OR
did the implementation fail to validate an in-domain typed value the
docs are silent about?" The first is caller misuse (`{{ results_dir }}/findings/`
at most, often nothing); the second is an API-hardening bug and belongs in
`{{ results_dir }}/crashes/`. **API-hardening bugs are the dominant bug class in
mature C/C++ libraries â€” do not gate them out.**

If you are unsure whether a value is in-domain: it is. A negative
`regmatch_t.rm_so` is an `int`; the type signature says all `int`s are
acceptable. The fact that no documented example uses one is irrelevant.

Do not file the following in `{{ results_dir }}/crashes/`: testcases where the harness
itself directly writes into private struct fields, links against
test-only TU symbols, calls a free function on a clearly stale
pointer that the public docs say must not be reused, or **misdescribes
its OWN buffer** to the API â€” pointing the API at a read length or write
capacity beyond the buffer the testcase actually allocated, or handing a
non-NUL-terminated allocation to an API whose public contract requires a
NUL-terminated C string. What the testcase tells the API about its own
buffer â€” the readable / writable extent, and whether it is terminated â€”
must match what it actually allocated. Deriving that size from untrusted
input is fine; the misuse is claiming the buffer is larger, longer, or
terminated when it is not. Those are harness artifacts.

This is distinct from â€” and you MUST still file â€” a length that measures
the untrusted DATA the library was handed, which it then reads PAST while
honoring an accurate value (a length-delimited API that ignores its
`len`), or a destination capacity the testcase passes truthfully that the
library overruns anyway. The test is whose promise the mis-sizing breaks:
the testcase lying about its own buffer (misuse) versus the library
failing to honor a truthful length/capacity for the untrusted data it was
given (real API-hardening bug). Everything else â€” including ugly-looking
inputs that nobody would write on purpose â€” file.

**Debug-only assert aborts are not crashes.** An abort from
`assert(...)` (`__assert_rtn` / `__assert_fail` in the trace), any
`[A-Z_]*(?:ASSERT|CHECK)` macro the project compiles out in release,
or Rust `debug_assert!` doesn't ship to users. Sanitizer hits on
those go in `{{ results_dir }}/findings/` at most, and only when you
can name the unchecked OOB / UAF / type-confusion / boundary cross
that follows in release once the assert is compiled out. The same
rule applies to FINDINGs.

**Build sanitizer trees as optimized release builds with symbols, not debug.**
When building a sanitizer binary or library yourself: use
`-O2 -g1 -DNDEBUG` (line tables only â€” clang and gcc both accept it; plain `-g` also works)
with sanitizer flags in compile and link flags; cmake
`-DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release`, meson `--buildtype=release -Db_ndebug=true`,
and autotools without `--enable-debug` (pass `--disable-debug` when
available). Don't pass `RelWithDebInfo`, `debugoptimized`, project-specific
`*_DEBUG=ON` toggles, or `-DDEBUG` / `-DDEBUGBUILD` / `-UNDEBUG` flags.
Debug-profile builds enable the very asserts you must not promote.

Every `{{ results_dir }}/crashes/CRASH-*/report.md` must include these exact fields:

Boundary:
Caller controls:
Trusted caller actions:
Caller contract: <fill in>
Trigger source: <fill in>
